abstract: The Napoleon Diamond Snuff Box Sold. abstract: From the Rochester American, June 27, A trial of Mowing Machines, under the direction of the Monroe County AgrIcultural Society took place yesterday afternoon on Judge BUELL'S farm, a short distance west of this city. There was present a very large concourse of farmers from all parts of the country, as will as hundreds of spectators from this city, all curious to witness so interesting a contest.

abstract: [Advetisement.] ORYSTAL PALACE.--WASHINGTONEA GIGANTEA, FOR MONSTER TREE OF CALIFORNIA !--An enormous, specimen of the Forest Giants of California, transcending in size and beauty any "big tree" as yet imported from that region, has just arrived from San Francisco, and will be exhibited in the Crystal Palace, which has been engaged by the proprietor of this wonder of nature, as the only building in New-York large enough to display its magnificent proportions.

abstract: From the Albany Journal, June 29. BENJAMIN HOFFMAN died this morning. He has been, for several years, afflicted with a pulmonary disease, and its termination, fatally, has been anticipated for many months. Mr. HOFFMAN was one of the proprietors of the Evening Journal from 1831 to 1842, since which time he has lived a quiet and retired life, in the enjoyment of a competency.

abstract: The Herald throws cold water on the project of the liquor-dealers to start a new daily paper in this City. abstract: The Old School' Presbyterian Assembly have formally discontinued correspondence with the General Association of Connecticut, on the following grounds: The General Association of Connecticut adopted resolutions, wherein they charge that the " silence of the supreme judicatories of the Presbyterian Churches in correspondence with them," in regard to certain legislation of our National Government, "gives painful evidence of delinquency in respect to principles and symoathis that are essential to Christian integrity."

abstract: The Know-Nothing party opened the campaignhere last week by a grand State Council, convened for the nomination of State officers. The sessions were secret, of course, and all that is vouchsafed to an " outside barbarian" is the poor crumbs dropped at the street corners, and in the social bar-room gatherings. Your correspondent has gathered up a few of the more important. Judge SHORTRIDGE is the nominee for Governor.

abstract: The Brooklyn Suicides. The Coroner's Jury adjourned to meet last evening to continue their investigation of this lamentable affair. At the hour appointed Coroner REDDING was present and all but one of the jurors. The absent juror was waited for a long time, and not appearing, the inquest adjourned to meet again on Tuesday afternoon next at 3 o'clock.

abstract: The act of March 4, 1855, gives away forty millions of acres of land. They are turning out land warrants at Washington at the rate of some hundreds a week. As those thus far issued are for the largest amounts granted--namely, of 120 and 160 acres apiece--it may be safe to say that ten millions of acres of public land have already been placed in private hands.
